<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-756-822  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 756 822.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Sept 28 1989 v15 n20 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Discovering the mail utility on your system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Clermont, Sylvain.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Every major mainframe computer operating system, including Unix,VMS and MPE, contains a mail utility.andP;  These electronic mailsystems constitute a valuable communication facility andproductivity resource.andP;  Mail utilities provide a simple way ofdelivering a message without interruption.andP;  Some systems featurereply commands that facilitate quick response.andP;  Unix systemsrunning on the X.400 and X.500 protocols offer the promise of aworldwide message distribution network.andP;  In addition, electronicmail systems offer new ways of collaborating with others on anetwork, organizing materials, managing information and reducingthe flow of paper that can be so detrimental to staffproductivity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsInformation SystemsUtility Programs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>